@page "/how-it-works"
@attribute [AllowAnonymous]

<PageMeta Title="How ScamAlert works — protect a loved one's PC"
          Description="You sign up and install on their Windows PC. ScamAlert texts you when suspicious remote access is detected—they do not have to monitor it."
          CanonicalPath="/how-it-works" />

<h1 class="h3 mb-3">How ScamAlert works</h1>
<p class="lead text-secondary">
    ScamAlert is for <strong>you</strong>—the person who cares for someone who should not have to fight tech-support scams alone—watching their Windows PC
    while <strong>you</strong> receive the alerts.
</p>

<div class="row g-4 mb-5">
    <div class="col-lg-8">
        <ol class="sa-steps">
            <li>
                <strong>You create the account.</strong>
                Sign up for $7.99/month and add <em>your</em> mobile (and an optional backup) as the people who get SMS alerts.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Install on their PC—not yours.</strong>
                Download the Windows app on the PC they use every day. Pair it to your account with a one-time code from your dashboard.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>We watch remote-access paths on that machine.</strong>
                When someone tries to connect to that PC remotely (the same kinds of access scammers abuse), the PC lets your account know.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>You get the text—not a call center.</strong>
                Alerts go to the numbers you listed. If the first person does not respond, we can text the next contact you added.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>You call and help.</strong>
                Check whether they expected someone on their PC, help them hang up on the scammer, or secure the machine. They do not need to check a website for alerts—you get the text.
            </li>
        </ol>
    </div>
    <div class="col-lg-4">
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-body">
                <h2 class="h6">What we are (and are not)</h2>
                <ul class="small text-secondary mb-0">
                    <li class="mb-2"><strong>We are</strong> an early-warning layer on PCs you install for people you care about.</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><strong>We are not</strong> antivirus, a VPN, or a guarantee that scams will never succeed.</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><strong>We are not</strong> a service that reads their email or browsing history.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="sa-muted-panel rounded p-4 mb-4">
    <h2 class="h5">Why people use ScamAlert</h2>
    <p class="text-secondary mb-0">
        Refund scams and fake tech support often end with “install this so we can help.” If that happens while you are at work or in another state,
        ScamAlert gives <em>you</em> a chance to notice and call back before a session turns into gift cards or drained accounts.
    </p>
</div>

<p class="mb-0">
    <a class="btn btn-primary me-2" href="/signup">Protect someone I care for</a>
    <a class="btn btn-outline-secondary" href="/faq">Read FAQ</a>
</p>
